{
  "Isotopes of an element differ in their number of:": "",
  "Protons": "",
  "Neutrons": "",
  "Valence electrons": "",
  "Electrons": "",
  "Isotopes have the same number of protons (same element) but different numbers of neutrons, giving them different mass numbers.": "",
  "Carbon-12 and Carbon-14 have the same number of:": "",
  "Protons (6 each)": "",
  "Total nucleons": "",
  "Mass numbers": "",
  "Both are carbon isotopes with 6 protons. C-12 has 6 neutrons while C-14 has 8 neutrons, giving different mass numbers.": "",
  "Which hydrogen isotope has one neutron?": "",
  "Deuterium (H-2)": "",
  "Protium (H-1)": "",
  "Helium-3": "",
  "Tritium (H-3)": "",
  "Deuterium has 1 proton and 1 neutron (mass number 2). Protium has 0 neutrons; tritium has 2 neutrons.": "",
  "A radioisotope is an isotope that:": "",
  "Is always synthetic": "",
  "Has no neutrons": "",
  "Is unstable and undergoes radioactive decay": "",
  "Is completely stable": "",
  "Radioisotopes have unstable nuclei that emit particles or energy to reach stability. They can be natural (like C-14) or synthetic (like Tc-99m).": "",
  "The average atomic mass on the periodic table is calculated from:": "",
  "The lightest isotope only": "",
  "Only the most common isotope": "",
  "Only protons": "",
  "The weighted average of all naturally occurring isotopes": "",
  "Atomic mass is a weighted average: each isotope's mass is multiplied by its percent abundance, then summed. More abundant isotopes contribute more to the average.": "",
  "Carbon-14 is useful for dating organic materials because it:": "",
  "Is only found in water": "",
  "Has a half-life of about 5,730 years": "",
  "Decays in seconds": "",
  "C-14 is continuously produced in the atmosphere and incorporated into living organisms. After death, C-14 decays with a half-life of ~5,730 years, allowing dating up to ~50,000 years.": "",
  "Isotopes of the same element have identical:": "",
  "Atomic masses, particularly": "",
  "Chemical properties (same number of electrons)": "",
  "Numbers of neutrons as typically": "",
  "Mass numbers, particularly regarding": "",
  "Since isotopes have the same number of protons and electrons, they undergo the same chemical reactions. Their physical properties (mass, density) differ due to different neutron counts.": "",
  "What is the mass number of an isotope?": "",
  "The atomic number": "",
  "The total number of protons and neutrons": "",
  "The average atomic mass": "",
  "The number of electrons only": "",
  "Mass number (A) = protons + neutrons. It is always a whole number, unlike atomic mass which is a weighted average.": "",
  "An instrument that measures isotope masses and abundances is called a:": "",
  "Geiger counter": "",
  "Thermometer": "",
  "Mass spectrometer": "",
  "Spectrophotometer": "",
  "A mass spectrometer ionizes atoms, accelerates them through a magnetic field, and separates them by mass-to-charge ratio to determine each isotope's mass and relative abundance.": "",
  "How many neutrons does Oxygen-18 have?": "",
  "8": "",
  "2": "",
  "10": "",
  "18": "",
  "Oxygen has 8 protons (Z = 8). Neutrons = mass number − atomic number = 18 − 8 = 10.": "",
  "What is the definition of an isotope?": "",
  "Any radioactive atom": "",
  "Atoms of different elements with the same mass": "",
  "Atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons": "",
  "Atoms with no electrons": "",
  "Isotopes share the same atomic number (same element) but differ in neutron count and therefore mass number. Not all isotopes are radioactive — most are stable.": "",
  "What does 'percent abundance' mean?": "",
  "The rate of radioactive decay": "",
  "The total number of atoms in a sample": "",
  "The percentage of protons in an atom": "",
  "The percentage of each isotope found naturally for a given element": "",
  "Percent abundance indicates how much of each isotope exists in nature. For example, about 98.9% of carbon is C-12 and 1.1% is C-13.": "",
  "What is atomic mass (in the context of isotopes)?": "",
  "The number of protons": "",
  "The same as atomic number": "",
  "The weighted average of the masses of all naturally occurring isotopes": "",
  "The mass of the most common isotope only": "",
  "Atomic mass is calculated as: Σ(isotope mass × fractional abundance). It is measured in atomic mass units (amu) and appears as a decimal on the periodic table.": "",
  "What is the term for isotope notation written as Element-mass number (e.g., Carbon-14)?": "",
  "Lewis notation": "",
  "Bohr notation": "",
  "Nuclear notation": "",
  "Hyphen notation": "",
  "Hyphen notation (e.g., Uranium-235) uses the element name followed by the mass number. Nuclear notation shows the mass number as a superscript and atomic number as a subscript.": "",
