  "The color of a chemical": "",
  "The speed of electrons": "",
  "The temperature of a reaction": "",
  "The masses and relative abundances of isotopes in a sample": "",
  "Mass spectrometers separate ionized atoms by mass-to-charge ratio in a magnetic field, producing a spectrum showing each isotope's mass and how common it is.": "",
  "What is the unit used for atomic mass?": "",
  "Mole, particularl": "",
  "Atomic mass unit (amu)": "",
  "Joule, particular": "",
  "Gram, particularl": "",
  "One amu is defined as 1/12 of the mass of a carbon-12 atom. It is the standard unit for expressing masses on the atomic scale.": "",
  "Why is the atomic mass of chlorine approximately 35.5 amu rather than a whole number?": "",
  "Chlorine has fractional protons": "",
  "It is a weighted average of Cl-35 (75.8%) and Cl-37 (24.2%)": "",
  "The periodic table rounds incorrectly": "",
  "Chlorine atoms lose half a neutron": "",
  "Chlorine's two stable isotopes have different masses. The weighted average 0.758 × 35 + 0.242 × 37 ≈ 35.5 amu explains the decimal value.": "",
  "Isobars are atoms that have the same:": "",
  "Atomic number but different mass numbers": "",
  "Chemical properties": "",
  "Number of electrons": "",
  "Mass number but different atomic numbers": "",
  "Isobars are different elements with the same mass number (e.g., C-14 and N-14 both have A = 14 but Z = 6 and Z = 7 respectively).": "",
  "Tritium (H-3) is a radioisotope because it:": "",
  "Is the most common hydrogen isotope": "",
  "Has an unstable nucleus and undergoes beta decay": "",
  "Tritium has 1 proton and 2 neutrons. Its excess neutrons make it unstable; it undergoes beta decay with a half-life of about 12.3 years.": "",
  "A geologist uses potassium-40 dating on a rock sample. K-40 decays to Ar-40 with a half-life of 1.25 billion years. If 75% of the original K-40 has decayed, how old is the rock?": "",
  "625 million years": "",
  "2.5 billion years": "",
  "1.25 billion years": "",
  "3.75 billion years": "",
  "75% decayed means 25% remains = (1/2)². Two half-lives: 2 × 1.25 billion = 2.5 billion years.": "",
  "An archaeologist finds a wooden artifact with only 12.5% of its original C-14 remaining. Approximately how old is the artifact?": "",
  "About 11,460 years": "",
  "About 28,650 years": "",
  "About 17,190 years": "",
  "About 5,730 years": "",
  "12.5% = (1/2)³ = 3 half-lives. 3 × 5,730 years = 17,190 years old.": "",
  "A chemist needs to calculate the atomic mass of an element with two isotopes: X-10 (20% abundance) and X-11 (80% abundance). What is the atomic mass?": "",
  "10.5 amu": "",
  "11.0 amu": "",
  "10.8 amu": "",
  "10.2 amu": "",
  "Weighted average: (0.20 × 10) + (0.80 × 11) = 2.0 + 8.8 = 10.8 amu. The heavier isotope dominates because it is more abundant.": "",
  "A nuclear medicine technician prepares Tc-99m (half-life 6 hours) for a patient scan at 8 AM. By what time will only 25% of the original activity remain?": "",
  "8 AM the next day": "",
  "Noon the same day": "",
  "2 PM the same day": "",
  "8 PM the same day": "",
  "25% = (1/2)² = 2 half-lives. 2 × 6 hours = 12 hours after 8 AM = 8 PM.": "",
  "A mass spectrometer analysis shows two peaks for neon: one at mass 20 (90.5%) and one at mass 22 (9.5%). What is the approximate atomic mass of neon?": "",
  "22.0 amu": "",
  "21.0 amu": "",
  "20.0 amu": "",
  "20.19 amu": "",
  "(0.905 × 20) + (0.095 × 22) = 18.10 + 2.09 = 20.19 amu. This is very close to the periodic table value of 20.18 for neon.": "",
  "Heavy water (D₂O) is used in some nuclear reactors. What makes it 'heavy'?": "",
  "It contains dissolved lead": "",
  "It is denser because it is frozen": "",
  "It contains deuterium (H-2) instead of protium (H-1), adding extra neutrons": "",
  "It contains tritium instead of oxygen": "",
  "Deuterium has 1 proton + 1 neutron (mass 2) vs. protium's 1 proton (mass 1). D₂O has molecular mass ~20 vs. H₂O's ~18, making it about 11% heavier.": "",
  "A forensic scientist uses isotope ratios of strontium (Sr-87/Sr-86) in teeth to determine where a person grew up. This works because:": "",
  "Strontium is radioactive and decays in teeth": "",
  "Different geographic regions have distinct isotope ratios in soil and water": "",
  "Sr-87 converts to Sr-86 after death": "",
  "All teeth contain the same isotope ratios": "",
  "Strontium isotope ratios vary by geological region. Since teeth form during childhood and preserve these ratios, they serve as a geographic fingerprint.": "",
  "An element has three isotopes: A-24 (78.99%), A-25 (10.00%), and A-26 (11.01%). Which isotope's mass contributes most to the weighted average?": "",
  "A-26, because it is heaviest": "",
  "A-24, because it is most abundant": "",
  "They all contribute equally": "",
  "A-25, because it is the middle value": "",
  "In a weighted average, the most abundant isotope has the largest weight factor. A-24 at 78.99% dominates the calculation, pulling the average close to 24.": "",
  "A hospital uses I-131 (radioisotope, half-life 8 days) to treat thyroid conditions. Why is a short-lived radioisotope preferred for medical use?": "",
  "It delivers the treatment quickly and doesn't remain radioactive in the body for long": "",
  "Long-lived isotopes cannot target specific organs": "",
  "Short half-lives mean the isotope is not radioactive": "",
  "Short half-lives produce more radiation overall": "",
  "Short-lived radioisotopes decay quickly, minimizing prolonged radiation exposure. I-131 targets the thyroid, treats the condition, and largely decays within weeks.": "",
  "Scientists discover a new mineral containing element Z. Mass spectrometry shows Z-50 at 60% and Z-52 at 40%. What is the approximate atomic mass of element Z?": "",
  "52.0 amu": "",
  "51.0 amu": "",
  "50.8 amu": "",
  "50.0 amu": "",
  "(0.60 × 50) + (0.40 × 52) = 30 + 20.8 = 50.8 amu. The result sits between the two isotope masses, weighted toward the more abundant Z-50.": ""
